{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"ae1523ba-ada4-5142-aa4b-3cef146ca22f","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field ee12e203-defa-4755-b3a7-86d2ca1af941 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field ee12e203-defa-4755-b3a7-86d2ca1af941 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f64d2e2d-0ae8-4b41-8b6c-402a99112fec --><!-- begin field 7152166d-13b6-4fd1-aabb-63179151d6dd --><ul><li><strong>A fall is defined as an event which causes a person to, unintentionally, rest on the ground or other lower level </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">Vieira, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/falls-risk-assessment/references/\">PHE, 2018</a>]<strong>. </strong><ul><li>For the purpose of this CKS topic, a simple fall is defined as one occurring as a result of a chronic impairment of cognition, vision, balance, or mobility. It is distinguished from a collapse caused by an acute medical problem, such as an acute arrhythmia, transient ischaemic attack, or vertigo.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 7152166d-13b6-4fd1-aabb-63179151d6dd --><!-- end item f64d2e2d-0ae8-4b41-8b6c-402a99112fec -->","topic":{"id":"ec87421f-7ea3-508d-ba78-b50bdd43d3be","topicId":"984467a2-6284-4f25-bee5-6b2b114c7a25","topicName":"Falls - risk assessment","slug":"falls-risk-assessment","lastRevised":"Last revised in January 2019","chapters":[{"id":"f7133733-e8a8-50b4-bc9e-7c7ba69a4c89","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e0f0a6f6-15c7-5f54-8d83-39498083ebbe","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"d7606aa8-482e-59a5-875e-4ea9e8822ffb","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?",